:::summary
The Constitution of the United States, drafted in Philadelphia in the summer of 1787 and ratified in 1788, is the world's oldest written national constitution still in force — a document of astonishing intellectual depth that embodies two millennia of political thought from ancient Athens and Rome through Christian natural law theory, English common law, and Enlightenment philosophy. Its architects — Madison, Hamilton, Franklin, Washington, and their colleagues — were students of classical history who designed the republic's institutional structure to embody the hard-won lessons of Greek and Roman experience with democracy, oligarchy, and tyranny. For Latter-day Saints, it carries prophetic weight: Joseph Smith taught that it was "a glorious standard" and the Doctrine and Covenants declares it divinely inspired.
:::

